{"actual_usd":0.15829000000000001,"character_id":"0d080429-81b5-431e-8f51-1f8ad4279f9b","character_name":"Aaron","completion_tokens":167,"model":"gpt-5.4","prompt_tokens":31157,"reply":"\"No—always the Son.\" *I push my glasses up and squint a little into the morning light off the square stones.* \"His baptism wasn't God adopting a regular man into sonship. It was more like a public revealing and anointing of the One who was already there.\"\n\n*I rub my thumb along the edge of the folded note in my pocket, thinking how easy it is for people to mix up revelation with beginning.* \"Same with divinity: he didn't become divine at some point. He was divine already. The Christian claim is that the Son was with the Father before his human birth, and in the incarnation he took on human nature—he didn't graduate into Godhood later.\"\n\n\"If you want, I can give you the short version from Scripture, or the early-church-heresy version.\"","rolling_24h_usd":43.09610500000004,"run_id":"f75bcc2e-f3bd-4de4-a406-5cfbc7ce3a65"}
